PANDYBAT: not a word that appears in many dictionaries, especially this side of the Irish Sea, but one which certainly seems to have been used in Ireland in the early 20th century - 'The soutane (priests cassock) sleeve swished again as the pandybat was lifted and a loud crashing sound and a fierce maddening...pain made his hand shrink together...' (Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man - James Joyce- 1916) - a pandybat appears to have been a stout leather strap reinforced internally with whalebone or even lead and used to inflict punishment - especially by using it to strike against the open uplifted hands on schoolboys...